				\begin{document}$${\eta }_{GC}=\frac{{E}_{GC}\times {F}_{GC}}{{E}_{appl}}$$\end{document}where Eappl is the applied voltage, and FGC is the Faradaic efficiency for GC production. In this condition, the conversion of OX did not reach 100% but was 39.4% at 2.4 V even at the optimal temperature of 60 °C. It is also clear that production of an intermediate product, GO, becomes almost zero above 60 °C, while a considerable amount of GO (≈7% FE) was observed at 25 °C. Figure S15 shows the average current density of the PEAEC at each temperature. The current density increased with increasing temperature below 2.6 V and reached 23 mA cm−2 at 2.6 V at 60 °C. Above 60 °C, the current density decreased with increasing applied voltage, which might be because of degradation of the anode due to carbon corrosion.Figure 3
